1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,000
You're still here?

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:40,000
You're still here?

3
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:44,000
It's perseverance.

4
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:49,000
I started talking about how within physical security we care about the infrastructure support systems.

5
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:56,000
And by that I mean making sure that we provide a good clean supply of power, network, and HVAC.

6
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:02,000
So let's talk through each of these pieces, actually two of them in detail, power and HVAC.

7
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:06,000
And we're going to start with power.

8
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:12,000
And the goal within physical security is to have a good clean consistent supply of power.

9
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:18,000
And there's a few components that we need to talk about that provide that good clean consistent supply of electricity of power.

10
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:22,000
Let's start with UPS's uninterruptible power supplies.

11
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,000
UPS's are essentially giant batteries.

12
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:29,000
And they provide two primary capabilities for us.

13
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:36,000
One is that as soon as the power goes out they provide instantaneous but short term power.

14
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:41,000
And by that I mean the electricity is running through this giant battery on its way into the building.

15
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:48,000
And so if the power from the mains cuts then the UPS giant battery provides instantaneous power to the rest of the building.

16
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:51,000
But only for a short period of time.

17
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:55,000
The other thing the UPS provides is what we refer to as power conditioning.

18
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:01,000
There's rectification and other circuitry in within these systems typically that will clean up the power.

19
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:08,000
And what I mean by that is that alternate and current AC current, if you look at it on a oscilloscope it should be a nice perfect sine wave.

20
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:15,000
But if the amplitude is too high, the frequency is too high or too low, you get dirty power, spikes, things like that.

21
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:18,000
And dirty power, bad for equipment.

22
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,000
So UPS's can clean up the power.

23
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Now I mentioned that UPS's only provide power for a short period of time until what happens.

24
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Until the generator gets up to speed.

25
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:33,000
Because the next major device we have to talk about are generators.

26
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Typically very large diesel engines hooked up to an alternator.

27
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Now if we have this big generator that's able to produce power for the entire facility, why do we still need the UPS?

28
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:51,000
Generators being big diesel engines, typically they take time to spin up to get up to speed.

29
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:56,000
Sometimes 20, 30, 40, 50, even 60 seconds before they're online up and running and providing power.

30
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:04,000
And so our UPS has covered this short window from when the power from the mains is cut and when the generator is up to speed.

31
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:08,000
So that's the use of the UPS. Now generators.

32
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:12,000
Because they're big diesel engines, they require maintenance.

33
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:15,000
I've seen a couple of organizations that have had this problem.

34
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:20,000
They've bought a generator, they've put it out in the parking lot, they've never touched it, never run it for 10 years.

35
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
The power went out and what did the generator do?

36
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Nothing.

37
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,000
These things require maintenance.

38
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:31,000
Usually a good idea to power these things on at least once a month, do yearly load tests.

39
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Don't have to remember any of these exact sort of numbers for the exam, but do recognize that generators need constant maintenance, well-defined maintenance schedules.

40
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:44,000
You also have to think about what percentage of the building can the generator supply the whole building by itself?

41
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:47,000
Do you need multiple of them together? What amount of power can they supply?

42
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:50,000
And how much fuel do you have?

43
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,000
You have to think about how long of power outage are we expecting?

44
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,000
How long do we need to stay up and running for?

45
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:02,000
And you need to have at least that amount of fuel supply in a tank somewhere nearby.

46
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And related to this, you have to usually have contracts in place.

47
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,000
So if you know that you only have 72 hours worth of fuel on site,

48
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:17,000
you should probably have a contract in place that's going to get you fuel in less than 72 hours, 48 hours, something like that.

49
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:22,000
A lot of organizations recently learned a hard lesson related to this in Texas.

50
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:29,000
When the most recent cyclone came through Texas and knocked out all sorts of buildings and infrastructure,

51
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:37,000
lots of companies had backup generators and those backup generators were running and those companies had contracts with fuel suppliers in Texas.

52
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:42,000
But the hard lesson they learned is that when FEMA came in, when the federal government came in to help clean up the mess,

53
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
they made sure really important services like fire and police stations and hospitals had power.

54
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
They just took the fuel basically.

55
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:56,000
They basically said the fuel, I forget the proper term right now, but they said the fuels are as we needed for critical services.

56
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:00,000
And it doesn't matter what contracts you might have in place, we're using it for these critical services.

57
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:06,000
And so these organizations, even though they had fuel contracts in place, still ran out of fuel and their systems went down.

58
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:13,000
So a lot of these, a lot of companies now are looking at putting in place fuel supply contracts that are out of state.

59
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:17,000
Now, we now have to talk about a few different types of power outages.

60
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:22,000
These first two here, blackouts, faults. This is a complete and total loss of power.

61
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:26,000
A blackout is a complete and total loss of power for a long period of time.

62
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:31,000
And a fault is a complete and total loss of power for a very short period of time.

63
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:38,000
The next three, brownout, sags, dips and surges, these are about not complete power loss but power and degradation.

64
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:42,000
So a brownout is a long period of time of too low of voltage.

65
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,000
This is usually intentionally done by utilities companies in order to insert it instead of having a complete blackout,

66
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:53,000
they'll have a brownout where it's not total as much power as you want, but at least it's nothing.

67
00:05:53,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Sags and dips are short, brief moments of not enough power and surges are brief moments of way too much power.

68
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:03,000
Think lightning strikes.

69
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:08,000
The other thing we have to be concerned with with power is electrical noise, EMI, RFI.

70
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
These are examples of where we get noise on the electrical line.

71
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:18,000
And this is why we have things like shielding around our and twisted pair in our networking devices, stuff like that.

72
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:23,000
Let's now talk about HVAC equipment, heating, ventilation and air conditioning.

73
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:32,000
Our HVAC systems are what provide air at the perfect temperature, the perfect humidity and filtered into the building and into our data centers.

74
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:39,000
Now, happy to report you don't have to remember the actual temperature ranges, humidity ranges and so forth for the exam,

75
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:43,000
but you do need to know roughly what these HVAC systems are for.

76
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:50,000
So number one, they provide air at the right temperature, because especially we as people we like air to be the right temperature, or else we're miserable,

77
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:54,000
but we also use air within a data center, for instance, to do what?

78
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:59,000
Well, that air is being brought, that cool air is being brought into the data center to cool the equipment.

79
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:04,000
It's all being sucked through the front of the server, run through the heat sinks at a server and exhaust it out the back.

80
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:10,000
So that air has to be the right temperature in order to properly cool the servers and keep them from overheating.

81
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:13,000
We also have to provide air at the right humidity.

82
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:17,000
What happens if the air is too dry, if there's not enough humidity?

83
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:20,000
You get static, you get shorts.

84
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:22,000
What happens if the air is too humid?

85
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:29,000
You get condensation, water and electricity, bad, so too low, static, too high humidity.

86
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,000
And then the final thing is air quality.

87
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:37,000
You want to remove contaminants, dust, debris, things like that from the air, filter the air before it's brought into the data center.

88
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:42,000
For that reason, I already talked about why do we bring air into a data center to cool the servers?

89
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:47,000
And if that air has dust, dirt, debris in it, you're going to be sucking that air through the servers,

90
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:54,000
clogging the heat sinks, clogging the system up with dirt and debris, they're going to overheat, short out, bad.

91
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:59,000
And there's one final bit of terminology you should be aware of related to HVAC systems.

92
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
And that is positive pressurization.

93
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:09,000
And this is the idea that we want to pump the air into the building, into the, especially the data center, at slightly above ambient pressure.

94
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,000
Not much, but a little bit.

95
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:12,000
And you probably experience this.

96
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:19,000
If you walk into a mall or something like that and you open the door and you get this rush of air coming at you, that's positive pressurization.

97
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:26,000
The reason we want that in a data center is that if the air is positively pressurized, if anyone opens a door, if there's any cracks in the building,

98
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:33,000
anything like that, you're forcing out nice, clean, filtered air and you're not letting dirty air contaminants come into the building.

99
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:36,000
So that's positive pressurization.

